 {"id":"bd-2wrsc.1","title":"[ALIEN-GRAVEYARD] Identify monotone vs non-monotone saga operations","description":"Audit all existing saga operations in Asupersync and classify each as monotone or non-monotone per the CALM theorem (Hellerstein and Alvaro 2020, Graveyard section 13.3). Classification criteria: Monotone = only adds information (inserts, appends, set unions, lattice joins, counter increments). Non-monotone = depends on negation or absence (deletes, reads-before-writes, threshold checks, aggregations over incomplete sets). Deliverable: Classification table in docs/calm_analysis.md. Methodology: (1) Enumerate all saga protocols, (2) List every step and side effects, (3) Classify using lattice test, (4) Identify minimum coordination points for non-monotone steps, (5) Compute critical path. Acceptance: Every saga operation classified, at least 30% monotone. TRACING / LOGGING SPECIFICATION: (Analysis deliverable -- define logging contract for runtime monotonicity checks.) INFO: CALM classification complete: total_steps={n}, monotone={m}, non_monotone={nm}, ratio={ratio:.2f}. DEBUG: step classified: saga={saga_name}, step={step_name}, classification={mono|non_mono}, justification={reason}. WARN: ambiguous classification: saga={saga_name}, step={step_name} -- step appears monotone in isolation but non-monotone in composition. Needs manual review. Metrics (runtime, for future use): saga_step_monotonicity (gauge by saga and step, 1=monotone 0=non-monotone), saga_monotone_ratio (gauge by saga), calm_coordination_barriers_total (counter by saga).","status":"closed","priority":2,"issue_type":"task","created_at":"2026-02-13T09:16:14.300951691Z","created_by":"ubuntu","updated_at":"2026-02-14T00:04:10.396418391Z","closed_at":"2026-02-14T00:04:10.396266439Z","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0,"labels":["alien-graveyard","analysis","calm"],"dependencies":[{"issue_id":"bd-2wrsc.1","depends_on_id":"bd-2wrsc","type":"parent-child","created_at":"2026-02-13T18:30:25Z","cr